ce:section.ce:para:
Herein, we report the direct current (DC) microplasma synthesis of bioresource-derived CDs with controlled structures and carbon hybridization states in a catalyst-free, environmentally friendly, simple, scalable, and rapid manner (Fig. 1
                     ). Suited for this study, glucose, fructose, sucrose, maltose, and citric acid were selected as precursors with varying structures-from simple sugars (pyranose vs. furanose) to disaccharides and a carboxyl-rich acid-and natural abundance, which favors sustainable CD synthesis. Detailed ex situ characterization revealed an intimate relationship between the physical (current and reaction time) and chemical (electrolyte types and concentrations) parameters of the plasma with the size and sp2/sp3 carbon phases of the synthesized CDs (Fig. 1 bottom). Moreover, in situ diagnostic techniques [26] including optical emission spectroscopy (OES) and absorption, were employed throughout the synthesis process to suggest possible growth mechanisms and engineering correlations (Fig. 1 top), providing a possible prediction over the synthesized product without heavy and time-consuming ex situ characterization. In situ OES focuses on the plasma properties (gas phase) such as plasma intensity and radicals, while the in situ absorption focuses on the precursor conversion into CDs. The results obtained can be directly cross-correlated to enable a quick study on the effect of plasma parameters (physical and chemical) on the CDs production and provide insights not only into the synthesis mechanisms, but also process optimization. As highly reactive species, OH radicals and solvated electrons (eaq
                     –) can subsequently decompose the carbon precursors into small moieties and initiate nucleation and nanocarbon growth. Our work provides insight not only into the synthesis of CDs from naturally available bioresources, but also into the engineering correlation between the plasma parameters and the structural properties of the synthesized CDs.
